    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, my apologies for the goblin confusion! Let's dive back into the 'spooky' part of quantum entanglement. The term 'spooky action at a distance' was coined by Albert Einstein, who was quite skeptical about this phenomenon. He found it strange and unsettling because it seemed to defy the usual rules of physics, where objects are only influenced by their immediate surroundings.\n\nImagine you have two magical, invisible threads connecting two distant, enchanted goblins. If one goblin suddenly changes its mood, the other goblin instantly feels the change, even if they're on opposite sides of a vast, enchanted forest. This instant connection, without any visible means of communication, is what Einstein found so 'spooky'. It's like magic, but it's actually a fundamental aspect of the universe that scientists are still trying to fully understand.\n\nSo, the 'spooky' part comes from the fact that entangled particles seem to communicate instantaneously, defying our usual understanding of space and time. It's like having a secret, magical link between two distant goblins that lets them share their feelings instantly, no matter how far apart they are. And that's what makes it so fascinating and, to Einstein, so 'spooky'. Hope that clears things up",
